August 2021 @ QJE

The Effects of the Minimum Wage

  • Perfect competitive labor market

    • Reduce employment, efficiency, and welfare (short run)
    • Wage and price adjust proportionately, money is neutral (long run)
    • Negative or neutral welfare effect

  • Monopolistic competition / Labor market friction

    • Inefficiencies in market allocation
    • Minimum wages reallocate workers to more efficient establishments
    • Positive overall welfare effect

The Effects of the Minimum Wage

  • Industries with inelastic demand

    • Increasing labor cost translated to increased prices
    • Possibly crowd out demand for other products
    • Possibly crowd out labor-cost sensitive businesses
    • Some are better off; some are worse off

  • Industries with elastic demand

    • Increasing labor cost translated to reduced profit, or bankruptcies
    • Reduced business profit and employment
    • Some laborers are better off; capitalists are worse off

  • International competition

    • Less competitiveness in international market
    • Either upgrade product quality or reallocate to other competitive businesses
    • Successful upgrade implies improved competitiveness and higher labor wages
    • Failure to upgrade implies less market share, less export, less domestic income

Bankground in Germany

  • Real wage inequality increased between 1995 and 2010
    • Real wage increased by 10% at the 90th percentile
    • Real wage declined by 10% at the 10th percentile
  • Workers covered by union agreements dropped from 80% to 55%
  • German government introduced a nationwide minimum wage in 2015
    • Initially 8.50 Euro in January 2015
    • Raised to 8.84 Euro in 2017, and to 9.19 Euro in 2019
  • Directly affected 15% of workers and 4 million jobs
  • Study shows the minimum wage account for about half of the recent decrease in wage inequality

Findings

  • The minimum wage significantly increased wages of low-wage workers
  • There is no indication that it lowered the employment prospects
  • The minimum wage reallocated workers to higher quality establishments with higher average wage, larger size, lower churning rate, and higher productivity
  • Minimum wages increased allocation efficiency of workers; though not all minimum wage workers are necessarily better off

Data

  • Individual-level German administrative records
    • Federal Employment Agency’s Statistics Department, merged with
    • Employee Histories of the Institute for Employment Research (BeH)
  • Include all workers covered by the social security system
  • Hourly wage before 2014; “proxied” hourly wage after 2014
  • Yearly panel from 2011 to 2016
  • Individual approach / regional approach

Labor Market Effect of the Minimum Wage: Individual Approach

Individual Approach

2-year Wage growth by wage bins

\[ y_{it}-y_{it-2} = \sum_k 1[b_{k-1}<w_{it-2}<b_k]\gamma_{kt} + \beta X_{it-2} + e_{it} \tag{1}\]

Confounding factor: mean reversion

\[ y_{it}-y_{it-2} = \sum_k 1[b_{k-1}<w_{it-2}<b_k]\gamma_{k2013} + \sum_k 1[b_{k-1}<w_{it-2}<b_k]\delta_{kt} + \beta X_{it-2} + e_{it} \tag{2}\]

Confounding factor: macroeconomic time effects

  • Subtract \(\delta_{kt}\) over higher wage bins
  • Treated group: (4.5, 8.5]
  • Partially treated group: (8.5, 12.5]
  • Control group: (12.5, +\(\infty\))

Full-time equivalents: 1 for full-time employment, 0.5 for part-time employment, 0.2 for marginal employment, and 0 for nonemployment.

Reallocation Effects of the Minimum Wage

Change of establishment quality

\[ q_{j(i,t)}^{l=t-2}-q_{j(i,t-2)}^{l=t-2} = \sum_k 1[b_{k-1}<w_{it-2}<b_k]\gamma_{k2013} + \sum_k 1[b_{k-1}<w_{it-2}<b_k]\delta_{kt} + \beta X_{it-2} + e_{it} \]

The “quality” of the establishments (measured only in \(t-2\))

  • Average daily wage
  • Share of high-skilled workers
  • Share of full-time workers
  • Wage premium (residuals from the wage equation, or firm’s fixed effect)
  • Churning rate (share of workers leaving or joining)

Churning rate is the combined number of workers who leave and join the establishments, divided by the number of employees at baseline. Poaching index captures the share of new hires whom the establishments recruits directly from other establishments, as opposed to new hires who join the establishments from unemployment.

Robustness and Heterogeneous Effects

  • The results are robust with
    • Individual-level demographic controls
    • Industry and location fixed effects
    • Local unemployment rate interacted with wage bins
  • The reallocation effects are similar in districts with
    • stable and declining unemployment rates
    • heavily and barely exposed to the minimum wage
  • The displacement effects are stronger for workers in
    • Food, cleaning, security, and logistics service (FCSL)
    • nontradable sectors than tradable sectors

Labor Market Effects of the Minimum Wage: Regional Approach

Regional Approach

Measuring exposure to the minimum wage requirement

\[ \text{GAP}_r =\sum_{t=2011}^{2014}\left(\frac{\sum_{i\in r}h_{it}\max\{0,MW-w_{it}\}}{\sum_{i\in r}h_{it}w_{it}}\right)\]

Event study approach

\[Y_{rt} = \alpha_r +\xi_t+ \sum_{\tau=2011,\tau\neq 2014}^{2016} \gamma_\tau\text{GAP}_r +\epsilon_{rt} \tag{4}\]

Difference in difference approach

\[Y_{rt} = \alpha_r +\xi_t+ \delta_{post}\text{GAP}_r\times\text{Post}_t + (\beta_\tau\text{time}_t) +\epsilon_{rt} \tag{5}\]

\(h\) denotes the weekly hours worked. The GAP reflects the percent wage increase necessary to bring all workers in the district up to the minimum wage. \(time\) is a linear time trend estimated from (4) with only prepolicy years.

Discussion and Conclusion

Discussion

  • This paper told a story of the “Swedish model” of centralized bargaining: government mandating higher wages drive low-performing establishments out of the market.
  • Reallocation increased market concentration and reduced competition among firms, which could potentially lead to higher prices and long-run welfare losses to consumers.
  • It seems the result indicates the labor market is far from inefficient: millions of workers can be reallocated to more productive establishments. But the effect is exaggerated.
  • Estimated 17% of wage increase can be attributed to reallocation, while 83% are wage increase within establishments. Businesses cut profit in the short run. But if businesses finally raise prices, it could potentially offset the benefit of increased wages. The long-run real wage effect is unclear.

Not everyone is better off…

Conclusion

  • This paper investigates the labor market response to Germany’s first-time introduction of a nationwide minimum wage.
  • The minimum wage policy pushed up wages without lowering employment.
  • The minimum wage led to a reallocation of workers to higher quality establishments.
  • The findings are consistent with a monopsonistic model of the labor market, where the reallocation came at the expense of increased commuting time.
